93-20180327-195122"/><CodeA name="rule" value="799599"/><CodeA name="rule" value="830688"/><CodeA name="rule" value="718028"/><CodeA name="rule" value="849154"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="2"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets><DescTPC fid="de"><DescField fid="ipc">N/GEN N/PLT R/NME R/NY R/NYC R/US R/USE </DescField><DescField fid="ipd">WSJ.com WSJ.com Site Search WSJAsia WSJEurope WSJ Japanese Online WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com BROOKLYN CORRUPTION BROOKLYN POLITICS NEW YORK CITY POLITICAL CORRUPTION SB123055822488121348798045841277216594953101 SYND CODES_REVIEWED NY Politics </DescField><DescField fid="ipcns">NYPO </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">US</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Ex-Brooklyn D.A. Hit With Conflict-of-Interest Fine; Charles Hynes will pay a $40,000 fine after he admitted using his work computer and email address for his failed 2013 re-election bid</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>New York City's Conflicts of Interest Board said Tuesday it had fined former longtime Brooklyn District Attorney Charles Hynes $40,000 for using city resources for his failed 2013 re-election bid.</Para><Para>The board said the fine was the highest in its 28-year history for violations relating to campaign activities. Mr. Hynes, a Democrat who served as district attorney from 1990 through 2013, admitted to using his work computer and email address for campaign-related business.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>As part of his settlement with the board, he also admitted asking his employees to do campaign work for him on city time. Mr. Hynes, who is now 82 years old, lost the race to Ken Thompson, also a Democrat, who died of cancer in 2016.</Para><Para>Using city time, personnel or resources for campaign matters is a violation of New York City law.</Para><Para>"In the midst of a feverishly contested primary race, I made the mistake of using my city email for campaign-related matters," Mr. Hynes said in a statement. His lawyer, Jim Walden, said the settlement "is hardly a foot fault in the epic match he played over 40 years of distinguished service to the public."</Para><Para>Mr. Hynes has long been dogged by accusations of misconduct. In 2014, a city watchdog agency found Mr. Hynes may have engaged in "possible criminal conduct" for paying a political consultant with what appeared to be assets seized during<ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/investigation-criticizes-former-brooklyn-district-attorney-charles-hynes-1401764141"> criminal investigations</ELink>.</Para><Para>Mr. Walden said federal prosecutors from the Eastern District of New York had investigated Mr. Hynes and closed the case without bringing charges.</Para><Para>A Brooklyn native, Mr. Hynes was long considered a power broker in the borough. After he was criticized for his handling of sex crimes in the Orthodox Jewish communities, he created a program designed to encourage victims to report sexual abuse.</Para><Para>Since Mr. Hynes left office, about a dozen people who were convicted during his tenure have since been exonerated as part of an effort by the Brooklyn District Attorney's Office to review old cases.</Para><Para>Mr. Walden called the problem of wrongful convictions a serious issue for every district attorney. "Hynes started the review of suspect cases in mid-2013, and I do not think he gets enough credit for laying that groundwork," he said.</Para><Para>In the board settlement, Mr. Hynes admitted to using his work computer and email account to exchange more than 5,000 campaign-related emails from May 2012 through Nov. 5, 2013. This included emails with political consultants, donors, political allies and campaign managers.</Para><Para>The emails discussed editorial-board endorsements, political donors, campaign advertising, opposition research, polling and numerous other matters, the settlement said.</Para><Para>The Conflicts of Interest Board also said it had fined four of Mr. Hynes's former staffers, including an assistant district attorney and a public-information officer. Mr. Hynes said his staffers did nothing wrong. "If anyone is to blame for this, it should be me and me alone," he added.</Para><Para>Write to Corinne Ramey at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:Corinne.Ramey@wsj.com">Corinne.Ramey@wsj.com</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Corinne Ramey </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ex-brooklyn-d-a-hit-with-record-conflict-of-interest-fine-1522173856" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

